Effect of the School Learning Environment on Studentsâ€™ Outcomes: Comparing Modern and Traditional Teaching Styles

This notebook examines the relationship between teacher quality, learning environment and academic achievements/wellness of students. Specifically, this analysis compares the mediation effects of teacher quality/learning space on studentsâ€™ outcomes through their attitudes towards math by teaching styles (modern and traditional). Methodologically, this notebook represents the results of the multigroup Structural Equations Modelling (SEM).

A set of variables under consideration:

  • Teaching Styles: TRADITIONAL (Teaches use layouts that support explicit instruction/ presentation everyday AND never need to rearrange tables, chairs or other aspects of the space (e.g.Â sliding partitions) prior to the start of a lesson because a previous user had them in a different position) vs.Â MODERN (the rest)
  • Math and Science Achievements, constructed as factor scores from five plausible values (TIMSS).
  • Wellness - factor scores from items on studentsâ€™ evaluation of their school (Q13 TIMSS).
  • Students Beliefs and Attitudes - a higher order reflective factor composed of 3 factors representing if students enjoy math, if they think math is important, and if they are good at math (Q16, Q19, Q20 TIMSS).
  • Teacher Quality - a formative construct, which included 2 reflective factors depicting if a teacher is understandable and if classes are well-organised (Q17, Q18 TIMSS).
  • Spatial Measures (SUS):
    • Technology - a number of learning tasks for which technology devices were used in a typical week.
    • Safety - a factor on manifest variables about feeling at ease in school.
    • Comfort Furniture - a factor on items about comfortability of desks/tables and chairs in the rooms students use.
    • Class Conditions - a higher order reflective construct composed of 3 factors: audibility (students hear everything clearly in the rooms where they have lessons), visibility (students clearly see everything that is shown in different rooms), temperature (temperature in the rooms is comfortable).

Exploratory View

The density graph below shows that students perform better in MATH, MATH APPLYING, MATH REASONING, MATH KNOWING if teachers exploit a modern style. The subsequent t-test reverberates this observation: the differences in mean math scores in the teaching groups discussed are statistically significant.

p1 <- stu_sus_timss %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = math_scores, fill = factor(traditional_style,

Further, we compare the mediated effects of Teacher Quality/Space on Achievements/Wellness BY teaching styles.

Analysis

We created factor models for each studentsâ€™ outcomes separately and established the modelsâ€™ measurement invariance to proceed with comparison. In all models, goodness-of-fit criteria indicated models of high quality. The models assume the existence of only indirect effects; therefore, all direct relationships were set to zero on theoretical grounds (e.g., teacher quality cannot influence learning outcomes without influencing students themselves, i.e.Â their attitudes & beliefs).

Green links depict positive effects, grey links â€“ the insignificant ones. The connections from the lower-order factors to the respective items are not shown (for readability purposes). Technology is the only observed measurement in the models. To calculate an indirect effect of a predictor to an outcome through a mediator, it is sufficient to multiply 2 coefficients â€“ the effect of a predictor on a mediator and of a mediator on an outcome.

To determine which structural paths vary between modern and traditional styles and which do not, we implemented a multigroup SEM procedure by iteratively constraining to equality the effects of interest and comparing the constrained and free models.

The main findings:

  • Teacher Quality positively affects all outcomes through improving studentsâ€™ attitudes towards math. This effect does not differ between teaching styles.

  • Technology (a number of learning tasks for which technology devices were used in a typical week) positively affects all outcomes through improving studentsâ€™ attitudes towards math. This effect is stronger for the modern style with regard to math, science, and (Math) applying.

  • Comfort furniture positively affects math, science, and (Math) applying through improving studentsâ€™ attitudes towards math only for the modern style; for the traditional style the association is not significant.

  • The rest of the effects are not statistically significant.
